<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[439,1837,1292,1950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">
This insect was very abundant in 
<collectingCountry box="[1150,1256,1652,1693]" name="Guam" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">Guam</collectingCountry>
, al&quot;':'ays on the 
<emphasis box="[1559,1605,1652,1693]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">ifil</emphasis>
tree 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kuntze" authorityYear="1891" baseAuthorityName="Colebr." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Intsia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bijuga">Intsia bijuga</taxonomicName>
),
</emphasis>
an important tree of the native forests, though a few stragglers were taken on other trees.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[439,1837,1292,1950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">
The species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crawford" authorityYear="1917" box="[728,888,1806,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Arytaina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variabilis">
<emphasis box="[728,888,1806,1848]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from the 
<collectingCountry box="[1344,1539,1806,1848]" name="Philippines" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">Philippines</collectingCountry>
by Crawford in 1917, without mention of food plant. It was later recorded from Malay and Borneo. No doubt it also occurs on 
<emphasis box="[1085,1319,1910,1950]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kuntze" authorityYear="1891" baseAuthorityName="Colebr." box="[1085,1313,1910,1950]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Intsia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bijuga">Intsia bijuga</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
as this tree grows there also.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
